r":"He covered the war from carriers and gliders","body":"During the Second World War Woodward set sports aside to report as a war correspondent. He rode with the 101st Airborne into the Netherlands and sailed with Task Force 58 off Iwo Jima.","number":4}],"sources":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST018","relationship":"alumnus","years":"1913-1917","institution_blurb":"Played tackle for the Amherst football team."}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[{"type":"historical_connection","related_id":"X00126","display_label":"helped found Yale, one of the colleges Woodward dubbed ivy"},{"type":"historical_connection","related_id":"X00613","display_label":"led Princeton, one of the colleges Woodward dubbed ivy"},{"type":"parallel_careers","related_id":"HD5949","display_label":"the Hall of Fame high-school basketball coach"}],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Rufus Stanley","last_name":"Woodward","display_name":"Stanley Woodward","gender":"male","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1780795180/Rufus_Stanley_Woodward_1895-1965_mlnmz5.png"},"military_service":[],"education":[{"institution_id":"INST018","type":"college","dates":"1913-1917"}],"career":[{"role":"Sports Editor","organization":"New York Herald Tribune","start_year":1938,"end_year":1962}],"slug":"rufus-stanley-woodward-1895"},"HD5929":{"id":"HD5929","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"gender":"female","birth":{"year":1898,"month":2,"day":10,"city":"Worcester","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1977,"month":12,"state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"is_easter_egg":false,"generation_from_thomas":10},"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["illustrator","author"],"notable_blurb":"Children's illustrator, twice a Caldecott Honor winner","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hildegard_Woodward"},"parents":{"father_id":"HD5926","mother_id":"I01581"},"number_of_marriages":0,"marriages":[],"tags":["painter"],"narrative_blocks":[{"category":"arts","header":"Twice she won a Caldecott Honor","body":"Hildegard Woodward earned Caldecott Honors for illustrating Roger and the Fox in 1948 and The Wild Birthday Cake in 1950, both written by Lavinia Riker Davis. She illustrated dozens of children's books and wrote several of her own.","number":1},{"category":"character","header":"Going blind, she learned to paint by touch","body":"When diabetes took her sight in her later years, Woodward refused to stop, devising a way to paint by touch with twigs and waxed paper. A friend mixed colors into numbered pots so she could feel which one she was using.","number":2},{"category":"legacy","header":"She left a mural in a school cafeteria","body":"In 1953 Woodward painted a long mural along a wall of the Center School cafeteria in Brookfield, Connecticut, near her home. Children watched from the foot of the scaffolding as she hid a dragonfly and a mouse for them to find.","number":3},{"category":"career","header":"A Boston illustrator drew her into books","body":"Trained at the Museum of Fine Arts School in Boston and in Paris, Woodward was introduced to book illustration by the artist Marguerite Davis. Her first commission came in 1931, and she filled her apple-orchard house with visiting children ever after.","number":4}],"sources":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Hildegard H.","last_name":"Woodward","display_name":"Hildegard H. Woodward","gender":"female","married_names":[]},"military_service":[],"education":[{"school_name":"School of the Museum of Fine Arts, Boston","type":"art_school"},{"school_name":"Paris (independent stu