:"Woodward recruited him as Worcester asylum chaplain in 1838","document_id":"DOC005","link_text":"Rev. Thomas Hopkins Gallaudet"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Samuel Bayard Woodward","first_name":"Samuel","last_name":"Woodward","middle_name":"Bayard","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1780793869/bayardwoodward_hpjb71.png"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST022","relationship":"honorary_degree","years":"1822","institution_blurb":"Received an honorary M.D. from Yale College in 1822."}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"burial":{"cemetery_name":"Bridge Street Cemetery","city":"Northampton","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States"},"narrative_blocks":[{"category":"career","header":"He built America's first state asylum at Worcester","body":"In 1832 Woodward became the first superintendent of the new state lunatic hospital at Worcester, one of the country's first public asylums for the insane. Patients arrived from prisons and almshouses, some chained for years, and many improved dramatically under his care.","number":1},{"category":"legacy","header":"He founded and first led the future APA","body":"Woodward helped found the Association of Medical Superintendents of American Institutions for the Insane and served as its first president from 1844. That body would in time become the American Psychiatric Association.","number":2},{"category":"social_reform","header":"He crusaded for asylums in his gig","body":"Before Worcester, Woodward drove his gig across Connecticut urging the founding of what became the Hartford Retreat for the Insane. He pressed the cause from a seat in the state senate and introduced sewing and spinning as therapy for his patients.","number":3},{"category":"character","header":"He was said to resemble George Washington","body":"Standing well over six feet, Woodward struck contemporaries as majestic, so like George Washington in his later years that a Boston dining room reportedly fell silent as he crossed it. A public subscription paid for a portrait and a marble bust in his honor.","number":4},{"category":"science","header":"A historian consulted him on George the Third","body":"George Bancroft sought Woodward's expert opinion on the madness of King George the Third for his history of the United States. Woodward also lectured for temperance and called early for asylums to treat inebriates.","number":5}],"education":[{"institution_id":"INST022","type":"honorary_degree","dates":"1822","notes":"Honorary Doctor of Medicine from Yale College."}],"career":[{"role":"Prison physician","organization":"Connecticut State Prison","start_year":1827,"end_year":1832,"notes":"Physician at the state prison in Wethersfield."},{"role":"Superintendent","organization":"Worcester State Lunatic Hospital","start_year":1832,"end_year":1846,"notes":"First superintendent of the first state asylum in Massachusetts."},{"role":"First President","organization":"Association of Medical Superintendents of American Institutions for the Insane","start_year":1844,"end_year":1848,"notes":"The body later became the American Psychiatric Association."},{"role":"State Senator","organization":"Connecticut State Senate","start_year":1832,"end_year":1833,"notes":"Represented the Hartford district."}],"slug":"samuel-woodward-1787"},"HD2442":{"id":"HD2442","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":7,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"HD2432","mother_id":"X00803"},"tags":[],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1797,"month":7,"city":"Hadley","state":"Massachusetts"},"death":{"year":1873,"month":10},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00804","children_ids":["HD2463","HD2464","HD2